this place is a real time machine i used to visiting ppiptek almost every week due to indosat galileo hype s kid here so i remembered most of the exhibits there i had a impression that ppiptek was really fun back then as a child decades later back to this place visiting as a parent bringing my year old son as long as i could remember of the exhibits with additions here there are still the same like i used to play as elementary student back then i jokingly told my husband that this place is an epitome of indonesias science condition undeveloped abandoned many of the exhibits here are broken places are quite dim its very sad to see isc in such condition last week we had a chance to visited petrosains at klcc i realized comparing isc to petrosains isnt quite fair considering the entrance fee at isc is very cheap but both of them are stateowned petrosains under petronas and isc under brin hoping this place will get a huge maintenance revitalization a lot of fund is needed tho since higher education considered as tertriary maybe

this place is a real time machine i used to visiting ppiptek almost every week due to indosat galileo hype s kid here so i remembered most of the exhibits there i had a impression that ppiptek was really fun back then as a child decades later back to this place visiting as a parent bringing my year old son as long as i could remember of the exhibits with additions here there are still the same like i used to play as elementary student back then i jokingly told my husband that this place is an epitome of indonesias science condition undeveloped abandoned many of the exhibits here are broken places are quite dim its very sad to see isc in such condition last week we had a chance to visited petrosains at klcc i realized comparing isc to petrosains isnt quite fair considering the entrance fee at isc is very cheap but both of them are stateowned petrosains under petronas and isc under brin hoping this place will get a huge maintenance revitalization a lot of fund is needed tho since higher education considered as tertriary maybe

tumurun private museum in solo is a delightful destination for art enthusiasts and families alike its smaller size and focused collection provide a unique and enriching experience the beautiful displays photo opportunities and the personal touch of a private collection make it a standout attraction in solo dont miss the chance to explore this cultural treasure during your visit one of the highlights of our visit was the numerous photoworthy spots throughout the museum the museum is a private collection from the family that owns sritex adding a personal and unique touch to the exhibits each artwork and item is carefully curated making the visit both educational and visually enjoyable a unique aspect of tumurun private museum is the strict time slot system visitors are only allowed to enter during their designated hour time slot this system ensures that the museum never feels crowded allowing for a more intimate and comfortable viewing experience to make the most of your visit its highly recommended to purchase tickets online in advance and arrive on time the museum itself is beautifully maintained clean and thoughtfully arranged the staff members are friendly and knowledgeable adding to the overall positive experience despite its size the museum offers a rich cultural and artistic experience that shouldnt be missed useful tip since the museum operates on a strict time slot system make sure to book your tickets online ahead of time to secure your preferred slot arrive a bit early to avoid any lastminute rush and to fully enjoy your allotted hour inside the museum

museum radya pustaka offers a profound glimpse into javanese culture and history its a mustvisit for anyone traveling to solo providing both educational and cultural enrichment we highly recommend it for families history enthusiasts and anyone interested in the heritage of java this museum housing a comprehensive collection of artifacts such as keris spears and wayang each piece tells a story of the rich heritage of java making it an essential stop for anyone interested in the regions history the museum is wellmaintained and the historical value it offers is immense we were particularly impressed by the wide array of keris and other traditional weapons each meticulously preserved and displayed the wayang shadow puppets collection is also noteworthy providing insights into the traditional art forms of java our visit was enhanced by the knowledgeable guides who provided detailed explanations of the artifacts and their significance the museums layout is visitorfriendly and the displays are wellorganized making it easy to navigate through the rich history of the area museum radya pustaka is one of the oldest museums in indonesia founded in the entrance fee is affordable making it accessible to a wide audience allocate at least hours to fully appreciate the exhibits photography is allowed in most parts of the museum so bring your camera to capture the intricate details of the artifacts
